BEAUTIFUL NOISE
A stage musical inspired by the music of Neil Diamond
Written by Paul Waldren
BEAUTIFUL NOISE is set in Manhattan NY in 1967. The hippy movement is in full swing,
civil rights are front and centre and Elvis and the Beatles have changed music forever. It has
also created a generational gap, more a chasm, between the older conservative generation
and their children who are embracing the new age of rock n roll.
Beautiful Noise is a story that tells the journey of a young 17 years old boy on the verge of
opera/classical music greatness. It celebrates music for what it is the most emotive and
natural form of communication in the world. BEAUTIFUL NOISE, at its core, is a story that
embraces the big band music of the time and rock n roll and meshes them together in a story
that celebrates the music of Neil Diamond.
Beautiful Noise will demonstrate that the gap between all forms of music is really a
subjective divide. One that should be transcended by our appreciation of the creativity in
many forms of music. This stage show will showcase the big bands not hide them under the
stage. They are an integral part of the show, as are the audience.
The SET: The set for BEAUTIFUL NOISE is designed to highlight and contrast the opera
versus rock dynamic. Stage left, we have our orchestra. The orchestra is on a turntable stage
and can enter and exit the set as required. Depending on stage limitations, some may by in
the pit. Contrasting this, we have a rock and roll band (guitar, drums, trumpet, keyboard) on
a turntable stage right. Both stages can be on set simultaneously, or individually. Back of
stage we have a choir to be used in support and for harmonies and is only visible when lit.
Our action takes place centre stage with a limited number of simple sets being bumped in and
out under darkness between scenes. Most sets will consist of one key backdrop, lighting
changes and some prop replacements.

SCENE 1 : THE CONFLICT (SET IN INTERIOR, FAMILY ROOM IN A NEW YORK
APARTMENT)
In this scene we open the show on Stage left. We see and hear a young man singing La
donna e mobile from Verdis Rigoletto as he wraps up rehearsal. It is an opportunity
for our audience to see the orchestra on stage. As the song completes, lights drop.
Centre stage is lit, and we see a mother and father discussing the upcoming
performance of their son Joel at a concert at New Yorks Lincoln Centre in the staging
of Puccinis Turandot. Some of Americas leading operatic artists will be performing
before Lance Markhoff, director of music at the Denmark School and famous
composer, as well as New Yorks leading Classical Music promoter Janelle Jonas. Many
are performing, but Markhoff and Jonas are there to see this young prodigy first hand.
Play La Boheme

DAD

In this pivotal scene, the crux of the plot is exposed that all music has some quality to

JOEL
Enough with the Nazis already! I didnt stop you from singing dad. Hitler didnt stop you.

MOM (now very upset and crying)

MOM
(calls after her husband) You cannot say that. Do not ever say that (the door slams)

JOEL
I know mom. But he cant control my life like this. He is killing my love of music, just as the

INTERMISSION
PART TWO
The second part of the show essentially provides the platform for a performance of
many of Neil Diamonds greatest hits. The mood of the show notably shifts from angst
and a conservative setting, to an upbeat, hit driven performance that involves the
crowd. One innovation to facilitate this is via a screen above the stage (previously un-
noticed that will provide the words to some songs performed by the cast and encourage
audience participation).
The show moves from Joels fractured relationship with his father to his developing love
for Caroline, but most importantly, his arrival as a singing sensation albeit not in
opera, but in popular music, and a whole lot more
In embracing his new self, Joel becomes so focused on his chance at stardom, he is
prepared to sacrifice not only his relationship with his father, but also that with
Caroline.
